t":"Fig. 22. TERRA-COTTA BOWLS. DESIGNED BY A CRIMINAL 134","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000118","text":"Fig. 23. ART PRODUCTION FROM PRISON 136","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000119","text":"Fig. 24. A COMBAT BETWEEN BRIGANDS AND GENDARMES. DESIGNED BY A CRIMINAL 136","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000120","text":"Fig. 25. A VOLUMETRIC GLOVE 224","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000121","text":"Fig. 26. HEAD OF A CRIMINAL. EPILEPTIC 224","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000122","text":"Fig. 27. ANTON OTTO KRAUSER. APACHE 236","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000123","text":"Fig. 28. A CRIMINAL'S EAR 224","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000124","text":"Fig. 29. ANTHROPOMETER 237","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000125","text":"Fig. 30. CRANIOGRAPH ANFOSSI 238","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000126","text":"Fig. 31. PELVIMETER 239","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000127","text":"Fig. 32. DIAGRAM OF SKULL 241","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000128","text":"Fig. 33. DIAGRAM OF SKULL 241","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000129","text":"Fig. 34. ESTHESIOMETER 245","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000130","text":"Fig. 35. ALGOMETER 248","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000131","text":"Fig. 36. CAMPIMETER OF LANDOLT (MODIFIED) 248","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000132","text":"Fig. 37. DIAGRAM SHOWING NORMAL VISION 250","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000133","text":"Fig. 38. DYNAMOMETER 253","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000134","text":"Fig. 39. HEAD OF AN ITALIAN CRIMINAL 254","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000135","text":"The preparation of the introduction to this volume was the last literary work which the distinguished author found it possible to complete during his final illness.]","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000136","text":"The first idea came to me in 1864, when, as an army doctor, I beguiled my ample leisure with a series of studies on the Italian soldier.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000137","text":"This idea, however, bore no fruit.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000138","text":"The second inspiration came to me when on one occasion, amid the laughter of my colleagues, I sought to base the study of psychiatry on experimental methods.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000139","text":"In homage to these ideas, I applied to the clinical examination of cases of mental alienation the study of the skull, with measurements and weights, by means of the esthesiometer and craniometer.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000140","text":"I, therefore, began to study criminals in the Italian prisons, and, amongst others, I made the acquaintance of the famous brigand Vilella.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000141","text":"This man possessed such extraordinary agility, that he had been known to scale steep mountain heights bearing a sheep on his shoulders.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000142","text":"His cynical effrontery was such that he openly boasted of his crimes.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000143","text":"This depression, as in the case of animals, was correlated with the hypertrophy of the _vermis_, known in birds as the middle cerebellum.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000144","text":"This was not merely an idea, but a revelation.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000145","text":"The various parts of the extremely complex problem of criminality were, however, not all solved hereby.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000146","text":"The final key was given by another case, that of Misdea, a young soldier of about twenty-one, unintelligent but not vicious.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000147","text":"Although subject to epileptic fits, he had served for some years in the army when suddenly, for some trivial cause, he attacked and killed eight of his superior officers and comrades.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000148","text":"His horrible work accomplished, he fell into a deep slumber, which lasted twelve hours and on awaking appeared to have no recollection of what had happened.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000149","text":"Misdea, while representing the most ferocious type of animal, manifested, in addition, all the phenomena of epilepsy, which appeared to be hereditary in all the members of his family.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000150","text":"Thus were traced the first clinical outlines of my work which had hitherto been entirely anthropological.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000151","text":"Finally, it was shown that epilepsy frequently reproduced atavistic characteristics, including even those common to lower animals.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000152","text":"But the first stone had been scarcely laid when from all quarters of Europe arose those calumnies and misrepresentations which always follow in the train of audacious innovations.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000153","text":"This is clearly shown in the third volume of _Criminal Man_, which contains a summary of the ideas of modern criminologists and my own.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000154","text":"They also initiated the practice, now in general use, of anthropological co-operation in every criminal trial of importance.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000155","text":"That ignoble multitude whom Dante relegated to the Infernal Regions were consigned by magistrates and judges to the care of gaolers and executioners, who alone deigned to deal with them.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000156","text":"This is the difference between the Classical and the Modern School of Penal Jurisprudence.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000157","text":"The offence alone was considered, and on it the whole existing penal system has been founded, the severity of the sentence meted out to the offender being regulated by the gravity of his misdeed.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000158","text":"It was these anomalies that first drew my father's attention to the close relationship between the criminal and the savage and made him suspect that criminal tendencies are of atavistic origin.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000159","text":"This vermis was so enlarged in the case of Vilella, that it almost formed a small, intermediate cerebellum like that found in the lower types of apes, rodents, and birds.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000160","text":"This anomaly is very rare among inferior races, with the exception of the South American Indian tribe of the Aymaras of Bolivia and Peru, in whom it is not infrequently found (40%).","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000161","text":"It is seldom met with in the insane or other degenerates, but later investigations have shown it to be prevalent in criminals.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000162","text":"This discovery was like a flash of light.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000163","text":"=FIG. 1 FOSSETTE OCCIPITAL (see page 6)=","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000164","text":"Thus also it was easy to understand why the span of the arms in criminals so often exceeds the height, for this is a characteristic of apes, whose fore-limbs are used in walking and climbing.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000165","text":"Subsequent research on the part of my father and his disciples showed that other factors besides atavism come into play in determining the criminal type.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000166","text":"These are: disease and environment.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000167","text":"Let us commence with the born criminal, who as principal nucleus of the wretched army of law-breakers, naturally manifests the most numerous and salient anomalies.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000168","text":"The median occipital fossa and other abnormal features just enumerated are not the only peculiarities exhibited by this aggravated type of offender.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000169","text":"The present volume will only touch briefly on the principal characteristics of criminals, with the object of presenting a general outline of the studies of criminologists.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000170","text":"PHYSICAL ANOMALIES OF THE BORN CRIMINAL","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000171","text":"The criminal skull does not exhibit any marked characteristics of size and shape.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000172","text":"Generally speaking, it tends to be larger or smaller than the average skull common to the region or country from which the criminal hails.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000173","text":"It varies between 1200 and 1600 c.c.; _i.e._, between 73 and 100 cubic inches, the normal average being 92.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000174","text":"The skulls of criminals have no characteristic cephalic index, but tend to an exaggeration of the ethnical type prevalent in their native countries.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000175","text":"=SKULL FORMATION FIG. 2 FIG. 3=","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000176","text":"In 15.5% we find trochocephalous or abnormally round heads (index 91).","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000177","text":"A very high percentage (nearly double that of normal individuals) have submicrocephalous or small skulls.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000178","text":"In other cases the skull is excessively large (macrocephaly) or abnormally small and ill-shaped with a narrow, receding forehead (microcephaly, 0.2%).","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000179","text":"More rarely the skull is of normal size, but shaped like the keel of a boat (scaphocephaly, 0.1% and subscaphocephaly 6%).","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000180","text":"2.) Sometimes the anomalies are still more serious and we find wholly asymmetrical skulls with protuberances on either side (plagiocephaly 10.9%, see Fig.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000181","text":"3), or terminating in a peak on the bregma or anterior fontanel (acrocephaly, see Fig.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000182","text":"4), or depressed in the middle (cymbocephaly, sphenocephaly).","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000183","text":"At times, there are crests or grooves along the sutures (11.9%) or the cranial bones are abnormally thick, a characteristic of savage peoples (36.6%) or abnormally thin (8.10%).","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000184","text":"Other anomalies of importance are the presence of Wormian bones in the sutures of the skull (21.22%), the bone of the Incas already alluded to (4%), and above all, the median occipital fossa.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000185","text":"Sometimes the forehead is receding, as in apes (19%), or low and narrow (10%).","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000186","text":"Prognathism, the projection of the lower portion of the face beyond the forehead, is found in 45.7% of criminals.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000187","text":"Progeneismus, the projection of the lower teeth and jaw beyond the upper, is found in 38%, whereas among normal persons the proportion is barely 28%.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000188","text":"(4.09 inches) as against 93 mm.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000189","text":"(3.66 inches) in normal persons.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000190","text":"Among criminals 29% have voluminous jaws.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000191","text":"The excessive dimensions of the jaws and cheek-bones admit of other explanations besides the atavistic one of a greater development of the masticatory system.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000192","text":"Asymmetry is a common characteristic of the criminal physiognomy.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000193","text":"The eyes and ears are frequently situated at different levels and are of unequal size, the nose slants towards one side, etc.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000194","text":"This asymmetry, as we shall see later, is connected with marked irregularities in the senses and functions.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000195","text":"_The Ear._ The external ear is often of large size; occasionally also it is smaller than the ears of normal individuals.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000196","text":"Twenty-eight per cent.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000197","text":"of criminals have handle-shaped ears standing out from the face as in the chimpanzee: in other cases they are placed at different levels.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000198","text":"_The Nose._ This is frequently twisted, up-turned or of a flattened, negroid character in thieves; in murderers, on the contrary, it is often aquiline like the beak of a bird of prey.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000199","text":"Not infrequently we meet with the trilobate nose, its tip rising like an isolated peak from the swollen nostrils, a form found among the Akkas, a tribe of pygmies of Central Africa.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000200","text":"All these peculiarities have given rise to popular saws, of a character more or less prevalent everywhere.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."},{"id":"swahili-000201","text":"_The Mouth._ This part shows perhaps a greater number of anomalies than any other facial organ.","author":"East African Proverb","source":"African Folk-Lore — Theal 1886","tags":["audience:morning","language:en","theme:community","theme:resilience","theme:wisdom","tradition:animism"],"isProverb":true,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Extracted from Theal 1886; verify attribution."}]}